Structures like this are common with API&#39;s that wrap all responses in some metadata-esque object. For example, given a C# class:

    public class Response&lt;T&gt;
    {
        string ApplicationMessage { get; set; }
        Exception Exception { get; set; }
        object Data { get; set; }
    }

By always returning classes that derive from `Response&lt;T&gt;`, the client code can inspect the metadata properties to gain further insight into the response, if necessary.

For example, let&#39;s say:

Request
-------

GET api.com/users/HunorKov&#225;cs

Response
-------
**400 Bad Request**

Body:

    {
        &quot;applicationMessage&quot;: &quot;Expected a userId, not a username.&quot;,
        &quot;exception&quot;: null,
        &quot;data&quot;: null
    }

The `ApplicationMessage` in this case gives details about why the 400 response was returned. Exceptions could be passed along for easier debugging in dev environments, etc.

For normal requests that have no issues, you&#39;d likely only see the data being populated:

Request
-------
GET api.com/users/1474495

Response
-------
200 OK

Body:

    {
        &quot;applicationMessage&quot;: null,
        &quot;exception&quot;: null,
        &quot;data&quot;: {
            &quot;userId&quot;: 1474495,
            &quot;fullName&quot;: &quot;HunorKov&#225;cs&quot;
        }
    }

